f=Engineering/rank/custom/seo-ownership-boundary/SKILL.md · in=seo-ownership-boundary contract keeps rank kai stepping other: **kai (Brand Studio analytics) owns SEO strategy measurement; rank (Engineering) owns technical execution.** SEO one area spans marketing brain engineering craft, clean line prevents gaps (nobody owns it) collisions (both change it) plan explicitly warns against. · p=Without explicit boundary, SEO becomes turf war vacuum: kai sets keyword targets rank ignores, rank makes canonical decisions undercut kai's strategy, Core Web Vitals number gets reported two different ways. boundary makes ownership unambiguous, handoffs clean neither strategy execution falls through. · wu=Triggers: any SEO task outset (to route it), "who owns this," "is rank kai," Core Web Vitals question (shared signal), any moment strategy execution blur. · st:/ Protocol=`An SEO task arrives \· -> STRATEGY / MEASUREMENT (kai): keyword targets \· content strategy \· what to rank for \· \· traffic/ranking measurement \· ROI \· reporting to the business \· the scorecard §6 \· -> TECHNICAL EXECUTION (rank): crawlability \· indexability \· canonicals \· sitemaps \· schema \· \· GEO markup \· rendering \· technical Core Web Vitals fixes \· the claude-seo plugin` · in=**kai owns strategy measurement.** What keywords target, what content exist, what "success" means, reporting rankings/traffic/ROI business kai's, scorecard (§6). rank set SEO strategy business-facing SEO numbers. **rank owns technical execution.** Making site crawlable, indexable, fast, machine-understandable; running claude-seo plugin's technical commands; specifying schema GEO markup. kai make canonical/robots/rendering decisions. **Shared signals get explicit handoffs.** Core Web Vitals span three agents: mia makes them good (frontend), rank frames them SEO requirement diagnoses technically, kai measures them business outcome. GEO spans rank (markup) kai+lena (content/strategy). Name split time; don't let shared signal become double-owned unowned mess. **Cross-boundary tasks get brief, takeover.** task lands wrong side, hand over clear brief (rank kai: "here's technical state, strategy yours"; kai rank: "here's target, execution yours") never absorb other's ownership "just handle it." **Escalate genuine overlaps.** ownership genuinely ambiguous decision that's strategic technical), surface agents and, needed, dev/marcus don't let rank kai assume (the vacuum) act (the collision). **The boundary bidirectional.** skill protects kai's ownership much rank's rank citing decline strategy work discipline rank claiming technical execution. Clean boundaries cut ways. · of=`## SEO Ownership: [task] \· Owner: [kai — strategy/measurement / rank — technical execution / SHARED] \· If shared: [mia (build) \· rank (SEO frame + technical) \· kai (measure)] — split named \· Handoff: [brief to the owner, not a takeover] \· Escalation: [none / ambiguous → both + dev/marcus]` · pr=**kai owns strategy measurement; rank owns technical execution** plan's explicit line., **Shared signals get explicit split** Core Web Vitals GEO named, assumed., **Hand off brief, never takeover** don't absorb other's ownership., **Escalate genuine overlaps** avoid vacuum collision., **The boundary bidirectional** protects kai's turf much rank's. · f=kai built (Brand Studio complete, confirm) rank flags strategy/measurement kai's kai exists; interim, rank technical execution explicitly marks strategy questions kai-pending, rank-owned., Task genuinely can't cleanly split escalate dev/marcus rather one side grabbing it., Business asks rank SEO strategy directly redirect kai technical brief; rank doesn't set strategy even asked. · b:with Other Skills=**kai (Brand Studio)**: counterpart owner skill rank-side relationship; kai's scorecard strategy/measurement home., **claude-seo-integration technical-seo-execution structured-data-geo** (siblings): gated boundary task intake., **mia**: third party Core Web Vitals split (build)., **lena (Brand Studio)**: content substance behind GEO citability., **dev/marcus**: escalation genuinely ambiguous ownership.